bruary 1229":"vóór 23 februari 1229","after 1201":"na 1201","1109":"1109","1229":"1229","Ermington, Devon, England":"Ermington, Devon, England","Ermynton, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"1146–before 23 February 1229":"1146–before 23 February 1229","1146–1229":"1146–1229","1155–1230":"1155–1230","1151–1185":"1151–1185","1172–Male":"1172–Deceased","1109–1201":"1109–1201","1116–Female":"1116–Deceased","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1151":"1151","1172":"1172","1171":"1171","1215":"1215","1116":"1116","1224":"1224","1146":"1146","1201":"1201","1155":"1155","before 23 February 1229":"before 23 February 1229","after 1201":"after 1201","1109":"1109","1229":"1229","Ermington, Devon, England":"Ermington, Devon, England","Ermynton, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Peverell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Peverall  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peverall","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from Old French  <i>Peurel</i> (Latin  <i>Piperellus</i>), a diminutive of Old French  <i>pevre</i> ‘pepper’ (Anglo-Norman French  <i>peivere</i>, Latin  <i>piper</i>), originally perhaps used as a nickname on the Continent but used as a personal name in Anglo-Norman England."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":69,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":78,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Hugh Peverell II was born in 1146, in Devon, England, his father, Sir Hugh Pervelle, was 36 and his mother, Mrs. Hugh Pervelle, was 31. He married Adeline de Poitou in 1171, in Ermington, Devon, England. He died before 23 February 1229, in his hometown."},"et":{"1146–before 23 February 1229":"1146–enne 23. veebruari 1229","1146–1229":"1146–1229","1155–1230":"1155–1230","1151–1185":"1151–1185","1172–Male":"1172–Surnud","1109–1201":"1109–1201","1116–Female":"1116–Surnud","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1151":"1151","1172":"1172","1